  {
    "specialty": "General Surgery",
    "topic": "rush.docx",
    "question": "With regard to hypokalemia, which of the following statements is true?",
    "options": {
      "A": "It is less common than hyperkalemia in surgical patients.",
      "C": "Hypokalemia can cause increased deep tendon reflexes.",
      "E": "Intravenous potassium administration should not exceed 10 to 20 mEq/h."
    },
    "answer": "D",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "COMMENTS: Hypokalemia is more common than hyperkalemia in surgical patients. Hypokalemia can result from increased renal excretion, prolonged administration of potassium-free fluids, hyper alimentation with inadequate potassium replacement, or gastrointes tinal losses. Respiratory and metabolic alkalosis results in increased renal potassium loss because potassium is preferentially excreted in an attempt to preserve hydrogen ions. Loss of gastrointestinal secre tions can also be a significant cause of potassium depletion. This problem is compounded if potassium-free fluids are used for volume replacement. Signs of hypokalemia, including paralytic ileus, diminished or absent tendon reflexes, weakness, and even flaccid paralysis, are related to decreased muscle contractility. ECG changes include flattened or inverted T waves, U waves, and prolongation of the QT interval. The best treatment of hypokalemia is prevention. Gastrointestinal losses should be treated by the administration of fluids containing enough potassium to replace the daily obligatory loss (20 mEq/day), as well as the additional losses in gastrointestinal drainage. As a rule, no more than 40 to 60 mEq of potassium should be added to each liter of intravenous fluid, and the rate of potassium administration should never exceed 40 to 60 mEq/h. Ref.: 1, 2",
      "A": "",
      "B": "",
      "C": "",
      "D": "",
      "E": ""
    },
    "guideline": "Source: rush.docx",
    "takeaway": "Key Concept: COMMENTS: Hypokalemia is more common than hyperkalemia in surgical patients. Hypokalemia can result ...",
    "id": 8
  },
