    "specialty": "Trauma",
    "topic": "Hemorrhagic Shock",
    "question": "A 25-year-old male is brought to the ED after a motor vehicle accident. He is tachycardic (HR 125), hypotensive (BP 85/50), and has a narrowed pulse pressure. He is confused and has a urine output of 10 mL/hr. According to the ATLS classification of hemorrhagic shock, what class of shock is this patient in, and what is the estimated blood loss?",
    "options": {
      "A": "Class II, 15-30% loss",
      "B": "Class III, 30-40% loss",
      "C": "Class IV, >40% loss",
      "D": "Class III, 15-30% loss",
      "E": "Class II, 750-1500 mL loss"
    },
    "answer": "B",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "This patient presents with Class III shock. Class III shock is characterized by significant tachycardia (120-140 bpm), hypotension, narrowed pulse pressure, tachypnea (30-40), decreased urine output (5-15 mL/hr), and confused mental status. Estimated blood loss is 30-40% (approximately 1500-2000 mL in a 70kg adult). Management typically requires blood products in addition to crystalloids.",
      "A": "Class II shock usually has a normal blood pressure and heart rate between 100-120. Mental status is usually anxious, not confused.",
      "B": "",
      "C": "Class IV shock involves >40% loss, heart rate >140, severe hypotension, and negligible urine output. Patients are often lethargic or obtunded.",
      "D": "Class III shock is 30-40% loss, not 15-30%.",
      "E": "Class II shock is 15-30% loss (750-1500 mL), but this patient is hypotensive and confused, indicating a more severe state."
    },
    "guideline": "ATLS 10th Edition - Hemorrhagic Shock Classification",
    "takeaway": "Key Concept: Hypotension and confusion are late signs of shock and typically indicate at least Class III (30-40% loss) in trauma patients.",
    "id": 794
  },
