    "question": "A 19-year-old male presents with 24 hours of periumbilical pain that has now shifted to the right lower quadrant. He has anorexia and a low-grade fever. Physical exam shows tenderness at McBurney's point and a positive Rovsing sign. What is the most appropriate next step in management for this patient with a high clinical suspicion?",
    "options": {
