      "B": "Aggressive fluid resuscitation with Lactated Ringer's",
      "C": "Prophylactic antibiotics (Imipenem)",
      "D": "NPO (Nothing by mouth) for 5 days",
      "E": "Immediate Cholecystectomy"
    },
    "answer": "B",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "The cornerstone of early management in acute pancreatitis is aggressive fluid resuscitation, ideally with isotonic crystalloids (Lactated Ringer's is often preferred over Normal Saline as it may reduce systemic inflammation). This helps maintain pancreatic microperfusion and prevents necrosis. Most cases are self-limiting with supportive care.",
      "A": "ERCP is only indicated within 24 hours if there is concomitant cholangitis or persistent biliary obstruction. This patient has no CBD dilation or signs of cholangitis.",
      "B": "",
      "C": "Prophylactic antibiotics are not recommended for acute pancreatitis, even in severe cases, as they do not prevent infected necrosis and may promote fungal infections.",
      "D": "Early enteral nutrition (within 24-72 hours) is actually preferred over prolonged NPO if tolerated, as it maintains the gut barrier and reduces translocation.",
      "E": "Cholecystectomy should be performed during the same admission for gallstone pancreatitis once the inflammation subsides, but it is not 'immediate' management in the first 24 hours."
    },
    "guideline": "ACG (American College of Gastroenterology) Guideline: Management of Acute Pancreatitis",
    "takeaway": "Key Concept: Aggressive fluid resuscitation is the most critical early intervention in acute pancreatitis. Prophylactic antibiotics are NOT indicated.",
    "id": 797
  },
