      "E": "Elective Sigmoid Colectomy after 2 days of IV antibiotics"
    },
    "answer": "B",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "Hinchey Stage Ib (localized abscess > 3-4 cm) is best managed with IV antibiotics and CT-guided percutaneous drainage. Abscesses < 3 cm can often be managed with antibiotics alone. This avoids emergency surgery and allows for a possible elective one-stage procedure later if indicated.",
      "A": "Emergency surgery is indicated for Hinchey III (purulent peritonitis) or IV (feculent peritonitis), or if the patient fails conservative management.",
      "B": "",
