    "specialty": "Cardiothoracic",
    "topic": "Tension Pneumothorax",
    "question": "A trauma patient develops sudden respiratory distress, hypotension, and distended neck veins. On exam, there are absent breath sounds on the right side and the trachea is deviated to the left. What is the most immediate next step?",
    "options": {
      "A": "Obtain a portable chest X-ray",
      "B": "Perform a needle decompression in the 2nd intercostal space, midclavicular line (or 5th space, anterior axillary line)",
      "C": "Insert a 32-French chest tube in the 5th intercostal space",
      "D": "Perform an emergent bedside thoracotomy",
      "E": "Intubate the patient and start positive pressure ventilation"
    },
    "answer": "B",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "This is a classic presentation of a tension pneumothorax. It is a clinical diagnosis, and management must not be delayed for imaging. Immediate needle decompression is the first step to convert the tension pneumothorax into a simple one, followed by definitive tube thoracostomy. ATLS 10th ed now favors the 5th intercostal space, anterior axillary line for needle decompression in adults.",
      "A": "Never wait for an X-ray if tension pneumothorax is suspected clinically; the delay can be fatal.",
      "B": "",
      "C": "A chest tube is the definitive treatment, but needle decompression is faster and provides immediate relief of the 'tension' mechanism.",
      "D": "Thoracotomy is for massive hemothorax or cardiac tamponade/arrest, not simple tension pneumothorax.",
      "E": "Positive pressure ventilation can actually worsen a tension pneumothorax by increasing the air leak into the pleural space."
    },
    "guideline": "ATLS 10th Edition - Thoracic Trauma",
    "takeaway": "Key Concept: Tension pneumothorax is a CLINICAL diagnosis. Immediate decompression is required before any imaging.",
    "id": 803
  },
  {
    "specialty": "Urology",
    "topic": "Renal Colic",
    "question": "A 35-year-old male presents with sudden, severe, colicky right flank pain radiating to the groin, associated with nausea and hematuria. A non-contrast CT shows a 4 mm stone in the distal right ureter. There is no fever, and his creatinine is normal. What is the most appropriate management?",
    "options": {
      "A": "Immediate Ureteroscopy and stone fragmentation",
      "B": "Extracorporeal Shock Wave Lithotripsy (ESWL)",
      "C": "Medical Expulsive Therapy (MET) with Tamsulosin and outpatient follow-up",
      "D": "Percutaneous Nephrostomy tube placement",
      "E": "Open Ureterolithotomy"
    },
    "answer": "C",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "Ureteral stones < 5 mm have a high probability (up to 80-90%) of spontaneous passage. In the absence of infection, intractable pain, or renal failure, conservative management is appropriate. Medical Expulsive Therapy (MET) using alpha-blockers like Tamsulosin can increase the rate and speed of stone passage. Straining urine and follow-up imaging in 1-2 weeks are recommended.",
      "A": "Surgical intervention is reserved for larger stones (>7-10 mm), persistent pain, or complications (infection/obstruction).",
      "B": "ESWL is an option for proximal/renal stones but is not the first-line for a small distal stone that can pass spontaneously.",
      "C": "",
      "D": "Nephrostomy is for 'infected' obstructed systems (urological emergency).",
      "E": "Open surgery for stones is extremely rare in the era of endourology."
    },
    "guideline": "AUA (American Urological Association) / Endourological Society Guideline: Management of Stones",
    "takeaway": "Key Concept: Ureteral stones < 5mm can be managed conservatively with MET (Tamsulosin) and hydration.",
    "id": 804
  },
  {
    "specialty": "General Surgery",
    "topic": "Acute Mesenteric Ischemia",
    "question": "An 80-year-old female with a history of atrial fibrillation presents with sudden onset of 'pain out of proportion to exam' and a single episode of bloody diarrhea. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender. What is the most sensitive and appropriate diagnostic test to confirm the suspected diagnosis?",
    "options": {
      "A": "Plain abdominal X-ray (KUB)",
      "B": "CT Angiogram (CTA) of the abdomen and pelvis",
      "C": "Colonoscopy",
      "D": "Mesenteric Ultrasound",
      "E": "Serum Lactate level"
    },
    "answer": "B",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "Acute Mesenteric Ischemia (AMI) must be suspected in elderly patients with AFib and severe abdominal pain despite a benign-appearing exam. CT Angiography (CTA) is the gold standard diagnostic tool, with a sensitivity of >90%. It can identify arterial emboli, thrombosis, or venous occlusion. Early diagnosis is critical to save bowel before necrosis occurs.",
      "A": "KUB is usually normal in early AMI. Findings like 'thumbprinting' or pneumatosis intestinalis are late, grave signs indicating bowel death.",
      "B": "",
      "C": "Colonoscopy is used for 'Ischemic Colitis' (low flow state, usually in the watershed areas), not for acute arterial mesenteric ischemia which affects the small bowel.",
      "D": "Ultrasound is limited by bowel gas and is better for chronic mesenteric ischemia (evaluating celiac/SMA velocities).",
      "E": "Lactate is a non-specific marker of ischemia and may be normal in early stages; a high lactate often indicates irreversible bowel necrosis."
    },
    "guideline": "ESVS (European Society for Vascular Surgery) Clinical Practice Guidelines on Mesenteric Ischemia",
    "takeaway": "Key Concept: 'Pain out of proportion to exam' + AFib = Acute Mesenteric Ischemia until proven otherwise. CTA is the diagnostic test of choice.",
    "id": 805
  },
  {
    "specialty": "Trauma",
    "topic": "FAST Exam",
    "question": "During the primary survey of a blunt trauma patient who is hemodynamically unstable (BP 80/40), a FAST exam is performed. Which of the following best describes the four views of the FAST exam?",
    "options": {
      "A": "Hepatorenal, Splenorenal, Pelvic, and Pericardial",
      "B": "Right Upper Quadrant, Left Upper Quadrant, Suprapubic, and Epigastric",
      "C": "Liver, Spleen, Bladder, and Heart",
      "D": "Morison's pouch, Perisplenic, Pouch of Douglas, and Subcostal",
      "E": "All of the above are interchangeable terms for the same views"
    },
    "answer": "E",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "The Focused Assessment with Sonography for Trauma (FAST) exam evaluates four potential spaces for free fluid (blood): 1) Right Upper Quadrant (Morison's pouch/Hepatorenal space), 2) Left Upper Quadrant (Splenorenal space), 3) Pelvis (Suprapubic/Retrovesical or Pouch of Douglas), and 4) Pericardium (Subcostal or Parasternal view). An unstable patient with a positive FAST requires emergency laparotomy.",
      "A": "These are the standard anatomical descriptions of the spaces.",
      "B": "These are the standard clinical descriptions of the window locations.",
      "C": "These are the organs being visualized to find fluid around them.",
      "D": "These are the specific recesses where fluid often collects first.",
      "E": "Correct, as all these terms are commonly used to describe the same 4-window protocol."
    },
    "guideline": "ATLS 10th Edition - Primary Survey",
    "takeaway": "Key Concept: FAST exam windows: RUQ, LUQ, Pelvis, and Pericardium. Positive FAST + Instability = Laparotomy.",
    "id": 806
  },
  {
    "specialty": "HPB",
    "topic": "Hilar Cholangiocarcinoma",
    "question": "A 65-year-old male presents with painless jaundice, weight loss, and clay-colored stools. Imaging shows a tumor at the junction of the right and left hepatic ducts, causing dilation of intrahepatic ducts but a collapsed gallbladder and common bile duct. What is the name of this tumor and its classification?",
    "options": {
      "A": "Courvoisier tumor; Bismuth-Corlette IV",
      "B": "Klatskin tumor; Bismuth-Corlette I",
      "C": "Klatskin tumor; Bismuth-Corlette II",
      "D": "Distal Cholangiocarcinoma; TNM Stage II",
      "E": "Gallbladder carcinoma; Nevin Stage III"
    },
    "answer": "C",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "A hilar cholangiocarcinoma (at the bifurcation of the hepatic ducts) is known as a Klatskin tumor. The Bismuth-Corlette classification describes its extent: Type I is below the confluence; Type II involves the confluence of the right and left hepatic ducts; Type IIIa/b involves the confluence and extends into the right or left secondary ducts respectively; Type IV involves both sides or is multicentric. Painless jaundice with a non-palpable gallbladder (negative Courvoisier sign) is characteristic of a proximal (hilar) obstruction.",
      "A": "Courvoisier sign refers to a palpable, non-tender gallbladder, which suggests a 'distal' obstruction (like pancreatic head cancer), not a hilar one.",
      "B": "Type I involves the common hepatic duct but not the confluence itself.",
      "C": "",
      "D": "Distal cholangiocarcinoma occurs in the common bile duct, usually causing a dilated gallbladder.",
      "E": "Gallbladder carcinoma typically presents as a mass in the gallbladder bed."
    },
    "guideline": "NCCN Guidelines - Hepatobiliary Cancers",
    "takeaway": "Key Concept: Klatskin tumors are hilar cholangiocarcinomas. Bismuth II involves the confluence of the right/left hepatic ducts.",
    "id": 807
  },
  {
    "specialty": "Colorectal",
    "topic": "Lynch Syndrome",
    "question": "A 32-year-old male is diagnosed with colon cancer in the cecum. His father had colon cancer at age 45, and his paternal aunt had endometrial cancer at age 50. What is the most likely genetic defect and the appropriate screening recommendation for his siblings?",
    "options": {
      "A": "APC gene mutation; Annual colonoscopy starting at age 10-12",
      "B": "Mismatch Repair (MMR) gene mutation; Colonoscopy every 1-2 years starting at age 20-25",
      "C": "STK11 mutation; Upper and lower endoscopy every 2 years",
      "D": "p53 mutation; Whole body MRI annually",
      "E": "SMAD4 mutation; Colonoscopy every 3 years starting at age 35"
    },
    "answer": "B",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "This family history fits the Amsterdam II criteria for Lynch Syndrome (Hereditary Non-Polyposis Colorectal Cancer, HNPCC). Lynch syndrome is caused by germline mutations in mismatch repair (MMR) genes (MLH1, MSH2, MSH6, PMS2). It is associated with right-sided colon cancers and extra-colonic malignancies (endometrial is most common). Screening for family members should begin at age 20-25 (or 5 years before the earliest diagnosis) every 1-2 years.",
