  {
    "specialty": "General Surgery",
    "topic": "Wound Healing",
    "question": "A surgical incision is undergoing normal wound healing. Which of the following represents the correct sequence of the phases of wound healing and the cell type that predominates in the first 48 hours?",
    "options": {
      "A": "Inflammatory, Proliferative, Remodeling; Neutrophils",
      "B": "Hemostasis, Proliferative, Maturation; Fibroblasts",
      "C": "Inflammatory, Granulation, Contraction; Macrophages",
      "D": "Proliferative, Inflammatory, Remodeling; Lymphocytes",
      "E": "Exudative, Proliferative, Maturation; Keratinocytes"
    },
    "answer": "A",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "The three overlapping phases of wound healing are: 1) Inflammatory (Day 0-4), 2) Proliferative (Day 4-21), and 3) Remodeling/Maturation (Day 21+). In the early inflammatory phase, neutrophils are the first to arrive (within hours), followed by macrophages by 48-72 hours. Macrophages are actually the most critical cell for successful wound healing as they coordinate the transition to the proliferative phase.",
      "A": "",
      "B": "Hemostasis is the immediate event, but the standard sequence starts with the inflammatory phase. Fibroblasts predominate in the proliferative phase (Day 4-21).",
      "C": "Granulation and contraction are part of the proliferative phase.",
      "D": "Sequence is incorrect; inflammation comes first.",
      "E": "Keratinocytes are involved in epithelialization, which starts within hours in primary intention but is not the predominant cell of the 'inflammatory' phase bulk."
    },
    "guideline": "Schwartz's Principles of Surgery - Wound Healing",
    "takeaway": "Key Concept: Wound healing phases: Inflammation -> Proliferation -> Remodeling. Neutrophils arrive first, but Macrophages are the 'directors' of healing.",
    "id": 810
  },
  {
    "specialty": "General Surgery",
