    },
    "answer": "A",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "Rigler's triad consists of: 1) Pneumobilia (air in the biliary tree), 2) Small bowel obstruction (dilated loops), and 3) An ectopic radiopaque gallstone (usually in the RLQ). This occurs when a large gallstone erodes through the gallbladder wall into the duodenum (cholecystenteric fistula) and travels through the small bowel until it lodges at the narrowest point, which is the terminal ileum.",
      "A": "",
      "B": "Pneumoperitoneum suggests perforation, not gallstone ileus. The duodenum is where the fistula forms, but not the most common site of obstruction.",
      "C": "Air in the portal vein is a sign of bowel necrosis or pylephlebitis.",
      "D": "Pneumatosis intestinalis suggests mesenteric ischemia.",
      "E": "This describes polyserositis, unrelated to gallstones."
    },
    "guideline": "SAGES (Society of American Gastrointestinal and Endoscopic Surgeons) Guidelines",
    "takeaway": "Key Concept: Gallstone ileus = Cholecystenteric fistula + SBO. Rigler's triad (Pneumobilia, SBO, Ectopic stone). Most common site: Terminal ileum.",
    "id": 811
  },
