    },
    "answer": "A",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "The Fogarty embolectomy catheter (invented by Dr. Thomas Fogarty) is a thin, balloon-tipped catheter. It is passed distal to the clot, the balloon is inflated with saline, and the catheter is withdrawn, pulling the embolus/thrombus out of the vessel. This is the standard surgical treatment for acute arterial embolism.",
      "A": "",
      "B": "Hickman is a central venous catheter.",
      "C": "Swan-Ganz is a pulmonary artery catheter.",
      "D": "Dormia baskets are used in urology for stones.",
      "E": "Malecot is used for suprapubic or gastrostomy drainage."
    },
    "guideline": "SVS (Society for Vascular Surgery) Practice Guidelines on Acute Limb Ischemia",
    "takeaway": "Key Concept: Acute Limb Ischemia = surgical emergency. Fogarty embolectomy catheter is used for rapid clot removal.",
