      "E": "Serum gastrin level; Hypergastrinemia"
    },
    "answer": "B",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "Hirschsprung's disease is caused by the failure of neural crest cells to migrate to the distal colon, leading to an 'aganglionic' segment. The gold standard for diagnosis is a full-thickness or suction rectal biopsy taken at least 2 cm above the dentate line. The biopsy will show: 1) Absence of ganglion cells (in Meissner's and Auerbach's plexuses) and 2) Hypertrophied nerve trunks (positive for acetylcholinesterase staining).",
      "A": "Anorectal manometry is a good screening tool (shows failure of relaxation of the internal sphincter), but biopsy is definitive.",
      "B": "",
      "C": "This is for Cystic Fibrosis (which causes meconium ileus, but not the Hirschsprung's transition zone).",
      "D": "RET mutations are seen in some cases, but not diagnostic for the disease itself in a newborn.",
      "E": "Gastrin is for Zollinger-Ellison syndrome."
    },
    "guideline": "APSA (American Pediatric Surgical Association) - Hirschsprung Disease",
    "takeaway": "Key Concept: Hirschsprung's = No ganglion cells in distal rectum. Diagnosis: Rectal suction biopsy.",
    "id": 818
  },
  {
    "specialty": "Plastic Surgery",
    "topic": "Skin Grafting",
    "question": "A surgeon is planning a skin graft to cover a defect on the face. Which of the following statements regarding Split-Thickness Skin Grafts (STSG) versus Full-Thickness Skin Grafts (FTSG) is true?",
    "options": {
      "A": "STSG has more primary contraction but less secondary contraction than FTSG.",
      "B": "FTSG is more likely to 'take' on a less vascular bed than STSG.",
      "C": "STSG includes only the epidermis and the entire dermis.",
      "D": "FTSG has better color match and less secondary contraction, making it ideal for the face.",
      "E": "The donor site for FTSG can be harvested repeatedly using a dermatome."
    },
    "answer": "D",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "Full-Thickness Skin Grafts (FTSG) include the entire epidermis and dermis. They have less 'secondary contraction' (the shrinking of the graft after it has healed) and provide better cosmesis and color match, which is why they are preferred for facial defects. Split-Thickness Skin Grafts (STSG) include the epidermis and only a portion of the dermis; they 'take' more easily in compromised beds but have significant secondary contraction and poor cosmetic results.",
      "A": "FTSG has more primary contraction (due to elastin in the dermis) but much less secondary contraction than STSG.",
      "B": "STSG 'takes' more easily because it is thinner and requires less revascularization.",
      "C": "STSG includes epidermis and a 'portion' of the dermis.",
      "D": "",
      "E": "Donor sites for STSG heal on their own and can be reused; FTSG donor sites must be closed primarily (e.g., groin, supraclavicular)."
    },
    "guideline": "ASPS (American Society of Plastic Surgeons) - Skin Grafts",
    "takeaway": "Key Concept: FTSG = better cosmesis, less secondary contraction (ideal for face). STSG = easier take, more secondary contraction.",
    "id": 819
  },
