    },
    "answer": "B",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "The rule for pheochromocytoma preparation is 'Alpha before Beta'. Alpha-blockade (usually with the non-competitive antagonist Phenoxybenzamine) is started 10-14 days before surgery to control hypertension and allow for volume expansion. Beta-blockade is only added after adequate alpha-blockade to treat tachycardia or arrhythmias. Starting a beta-blocker first can lead to 'unopposed alpha stimulation', causing a severe hypertensive crisis.",
      "A": "Starting a beta-blocker first is dangerous due to unopposed alpha-mediated vasoconstriction.",
      "B": "",
      "C": "Surgery without preparation is associated with extremely high perioperative mortality due to catecholamine surges.",
      "D": "Resection is typically unilateral unless the patient has a genetic syndrome (like MEN 2) with bilateral disease.",
      "E": "Calcium channel blockers can be used as adjuncts but are not the primary standard for blockade."
    },
    "guideline": "Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guidelines on Pheochromocytoma and Paraganglioma",
    "takeaway": "Key Concept: Pre-op Pheochromocytoma: Alpha-blockade FIRST (Phenoxybenzamine), then Beta-blockade.",
