  {
    "specialty": "General Surgery",
    "topic": "Refeeding Syndrome",
    "question": "A 22-year-old woman with severe anorexia nervosa is admitted for nutritional rehabilitation. Within 48 hours of starting enteral nutrition, she develops peripheral edema, confusion, and muscle weakness. Laboratory tests show severe hypophosphatemia. What is the primary physiological driver of this syndrome?",
    "options": {
      "A": "Glucagon-mediated protein breakdown",
      "B": "Insulin-mediated shift of electrolytes into the intracellular space",
      "C": "Acute renal failure leading to phosphate wasting",
      "D": "Vitamin D toxicity from nutritional supplements",
      "E": "Infection and sepsis"
    },
    "answer": "B",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "Refeeding syndrome occurs when a chronically starved patient receives a rapid influx of glucose. This triggers a massive release of insulin, which shifts the body from a catabolic (fat-burning) to an anabolic (carbohydrate-using) state. Insulin causes potassium, magnesium, and especially phosphate to move into the cells to support ATP production and glucose metabolism. This leads to profound, life-threatening drops in serum levels of these electrolytes.",
      "A": "Glucagon is high during starvation, but refeeding causes it to drop.",
      "B": "",
      "C": "The electrolytes are lost from the serum into the cells, not through the kidneys.",
      "D": "While vitamins are given, the issue is the electrolyte shift.",
      "E": "Symptoms can mimic sepsis, but the cause is metabolic."
    },
    "guideline": "ASPEN (American Society for Parenteral and Enteral Nutrition) Consensus Recommendations on Refeeding Syndrome",
    "takeaway": "Key Concept: Refeeding Syndrome = Insulin-driven shift of P, K, Mg into cells. Start low and go slow with nutrition.",
    "id": 825
  },
