      "D": "Nissen fundoplication; Wrapping the stomach around the esophagus",
      "E": "Heller myotomy; Dividing the lower esophageal sphincter"
    },
    "answer": "B",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "Bilious vomiting in a neonate is a surgical emergency (Midgut Volvulus until proven otherwise). The definitive treatment is the Ladd's procedure. Steps include: 1) Counter-clockwise untwisting of the volvulus, 2) Division of the abnormal peritoneal attachments (Ladd's bands) across the duodenum, 3) Broadening the base of the mesentery, 4) Placing the small bowel on the right and the colon on the left, and 5) Appendectomy (as the appendix will be in an abnormal location).",
      "A": "Kasai is for biliary atresia.",
      "B": "",
      "C": "Ramstedt is for pyloric stenosis.",
      "D": "Nissen is for GERD.",
      "E": "Heller is for achalasia."
    },
    "guideline": "APSA (American Pediatric Surgical Association) - Malrotation",
    "takeaway": "Key Concept: Bilious vomiting in a neonate = Volvulus. Treatment: Ladd's Procedure. Key step: Broaden the mesentery.",
    "id": 828
  },
