    "explanation": {
        "correct": "Courvoisier's Law states: 'In the presence of jaundice, if the gallbladder is palpable and non-tender, then the jaundice is unlikely to be due to gallstones.' Rationale: Chronic gallstone disease causes fibrosis and shrinkage of the gallbladder, so it cannot distend. A malignant obstruction (e.g., pancreatic head cancer, cholangiocarcinoma, ampullary carcinoma) causes slow progressive obstruction allowing the gallbladder to distend. This palpable gallbladder in a jaundiced patient is Courvoisier's sign and demands urgent oncological workup.",
